what works:
    - checkpointing a program with ./ckpt <executable>
    - reading a checkpoint image file (always named ckpt.dat)
      with ./readckpt ckpt.dat
    - restarting from a checkpoint image file with ./restart ckpt.dat

brief description of each source file's responsibilities:
    ckpt.c: 
        - preloads libckpt.so with setenv("LD_PRELOAD", ...)
        - calls execvp() to execute the given program
    libckpt.c:
        - uses a constructor function to register a signal handler for  
          SIGUSR2; the signal handler (sig_handler) also registers another
          signal handler (sig_handler2) to allow for multi-restart
        - saves and restores the fs register to avoid detection of stack
          smashing
        - saves all info from /proc/self/maps
        - saves current context obtained from getcontext()
        - writes (uses write()) all checkpoint data to a file named "ckpt.dat" 
            - the format used is header1, data1, header2, data2, ... where
              a header is a ckpt_header_t and the data is the raw bytes from
              those memory segments
            - the last header, data pair is a header with is_reg_context = 1,
              and the following data is the ucontext_t data from calling
              getcontext()
    readckpt.c:
        - reads each checkpoint header (defined as ckpt_header_t) from the
          checkpoint image file
        - prints out start and end address, permissions, filename, whether or 
          not it is a context from getcontext(), and data size for each 
          checkpoint header 
        - prints out all general registers that were saved in the ucontext_t
          from calling getcontext()
    restart.c
        - grows the stack with a recursive function with 1000 iterations
        - reads every checkpoint header and checkpoint data segment from the
          checkpoint image file
        - mmap's all memory segments in the checkpoint image file and restores
          the corresponding data to each memory segment
        - calls setcontext() to restore the hardware registers 

makefile usage:
    - make build: builds all executables as well as libckpt.so
    - make clean: removes all executables, libckpt.so and ckpt.dat
    - make check: checkpoint and restarts a program (./matrix)

note:
    - make check only checkpoints and restarts once; to test multiple 
      checkpoint and restarts (which should work) you can repeatedly 
      use ./restart ckpt.dat, sending a SIGUSR2 to checkpoint
